```class Solution {
    public int repeatedStringMatch(String a, String b) {
        int count = (b.length() + a.length() - 1) / a.length();
        String repeatedA = "";
        for (int i = 0; i < count; i++) {
            repeatedA += a;
        }
        if (repeatedA.endsWith(b)) {
            return count;
        }
        if (repeatedA + a.endsWith(b)) {
            return count + 1;
        }
        return -1;
    }
}```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(a.length() + b.length())
space complexity: O(a.length() + b.length())
energy implications: LOW
explanation: We efficiently solve this problem by first calculating the minimum number of times we need to repeat string a to make its length greater than or equal to the length of string b. Then, we check if string b is a substring of the repeated string a. If it is, we return the count. If not, we check if string b is a substring of the repeated string a plus the original string a. If it is, we return the count plus one. If not, we return -1.

